Yes — assuming the pxe-content image project and the pxe-content Ansible role both contain the changes we talked through, Phase 1 is basically code-complete.

Phase 1 is not “done-done” until you prove these things after merge:

1. The new image builds.
2. The role deploys the image using Quadlet.
3. The role mounts the bundle’s extracted_isos correctly.
4. The container dynamically generates content based on available ISOs.
5. The service survives reboot.
6. A real PXE client can still boot.

I would merge/test in this order:

1. Merge and test the pxe-content image project first

After merge, make sure the pipeline builds/pushes the image.

On the PXE host:

podman pull registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:latest
podman image inspect registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:latest

Then do a quick manual container smoke test before blaming the role:

podman rm -f pxe-content-test 2>/dev/null || true
podman run -d \
  --name pxe-content-test \
  --security-opt label=disable \
  -p 18081:8080 \
  -v /path/to/bundle/extracted_isos:/iso:ro,Z \
  -e PXE_SERVER=192.168.109.139 \
  -e PXE_PORT=18081 \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:latest

Then test:

curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18081/boot.ipxe
curl http://127.0.0.1:18081/boot.ipxe
curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18081/ks/rhel8-minimal.ks
curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18081/rhel8/images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18081/rhel8/images/pxeboot/initrd.img

Then clean up:

podman rm -f pxe-content-test

2. Test ISO detection behavior

Start with a bundle that only has this:

extracted_isos/rhel8iso

Then check:

curl http://127.0.0.1:18081/boot.ipxe

You should only see RHEL 8 options.

Then add or copy in another ISO folder:

extracted_isos/rhel9iso

Wait 10–30 seconds, then run:

curl http://127.0.0.1:18081/boot.ipxe

Now you should see RHEL 8 and RHEL 9 options.

Then repeat with:

extracted_isos/rhel10iso

That proves the watcher/generator idea works.

3. Merge and test the pxe-content Ansible role

After the role is merged, run it against the PXE host.

For your bundle layout, the important variable is the bundle root. Something like:

cd /path/to/aerolit_bundle_root
ansible-playbook \
  collections-hub/ansible/resources/playbooks/setup-pxe-content.yml \
  -i localhost, \
  -c local \
  -e aerolit_bundle_root="$PWD" \
  -e pxe_content_image_source=registry \
  -e pxe_content_server_ip=192.168.109.139 \
  -e pxe_content_host_port=18080

Then verify:

systemctl status pxe-content.service --no-pager
podman ps
curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18080/boot.ipxe
curl http://127.0.0.1:18080/boot.ipxe

Also check that Quadlet exists:

ls -l /etc/containers/systemd/pxe-content.container
cat /etc/containers/systemd/pxe-content.container

And verify the old handcrafted service is gone:

ls -l /etc/systemd/system/pxe-content.service

That should say it does not exist.

4. Reboot persistence test

This one matters a lot because it was one of the original problems.

reboot

After the PXE host comes back:

systemctl status pxe-content.service --no-pager
podman ps
curl -I http://127.0.0.1:18080/boot.ipxe
curl http://127.0.0.1:18080/boot.ipxe

Expected result:

pxe-content.service active/running
podman ps shows pxe-content
curl /boot.ipxe returns 200

5. PXE boot test

Then boot the PXE laptop.

Test in this order:

1. Confirm the AeroLIT menu appears.
2. Confirm only the OS versions present in extracted_isos appear.
3. Select RHEL 8 minimal since you already know RHEL 8 was working.
4. Then test RHEL 9.
5. Then test RHEL 10 separately, because RHEL 10 had its own package/signature/installer issue before.

For RHEL 10, do not assume a failure means the pxe-content work is broken. If it reaches Anaconda and starts package work, the PXE handoff succeeded. RHEL 10 package signature errors are a separate repo/content/signature issue.

6. Final Phase 1 pass/fail checklist

I would call Phase 1 complete when all of this is true:

[ ] pxe-content image pipeline passes
[ ] image pulls successfully from registry
[ ] role installs Podman/firewalld as needed
[ ] role creates /etc/pxe-content/pxe-content.env
[ ] role creates /etc/containers/systemd/pxe-content.container
[ ] role removes old /etc/systemd/system/pxe-content.service
[ ] pxe-content.service starts successfully
[ ] curl /boot.ipxe returns 200
[ ] curl /ks/<profile>.ks returns 200
[ ] curl /rhel8/images/pxeboot/vmlinuz returns 200
[ ] menu changes when extracted_isos changes
[ ] service survives reboot
[ ] PXE laptop sees the generated menu
[ ] at least one OS fully boots into installer

So yes: Phase 1 is code-complete, but not finished until those tests pass.

The main thing I would not do yet is start adding all the profile sets until this basic dynamic ISO discovery + Quadlet deployment path is proven end-to-end.